comments.message:
Not quite following this.  I'm assuming you're essentially doing the same thing as.

conn->callback = nullptr;

considering that tmp isn't used anywhere.  If we're needing to do this, we have some lifetime ownership issues that need sorted.  I suspect callback needs to own this connection by weak_ptr, not shared_ptr?

if this is really required, we generally write this as

if (satelliteInfo.empty()){
    return;
} 

to save on tabs below given our 80 character limits.

But in this case, is this check even needed?  Won't we just loop 0 times and be done?  Seems simpler.

This is still making 2 copies of the request, one as "req" and one as "localreq"  

I think you just want std::make_shared<crow::Request>(thisReq.req, ec);

Alternatively, if you really want the stack variable, make the line on 240 a reference, not a copy, but I think the former is still better, and drops a line of code.

need to check for pointer validity before dereferencing.

if (sharedReq == nullptr){
   return;
}

is enough.

this variable doesn't get used, maybe just loop over the iterator and check the length later?

for (const auto* segment: segments){
   segments.emplace_back(std::string_view(*it));
}

Also, as written, if I had something beyond 5 segments, doesn't this give the wrong result?

I'm surprised clang didn't flag this, but the std::string you constructed is already an rvalue, calling std::move on it has no effect.

I'm pretty sure you want:

segments.emplace_back(std::string_view(*it));
